{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01M2E3XFktUk2icn3uJZ12go","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The root cause is clear:\n\n1. The `es-config` ConfigMap has `node.name: ` (empty/null value) in `elasticsearch.yml`\n2. The StatefulSet has a `POD_NAME` env var that could be used to set `node.name`, but the ConfigMap just has an empty `node.name` field\n\nThe fix: The ConfigMap should either:\n- Remove `node.name` entirely (let each pod auto-detect)\n- Use `${POD_NAME}` to dynamically set the node name\n\nBut wait - the StatefulSet uses this ConfigMap as a volume mount. \n\nThe config file can't directly reference environment variables without processing through something like `envsubst`. What's puzzling is that es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1 are running fine despite using the same ConfigMap with the null node name, so either they were provisioned with a different config before this one was applied, or the node name is being set through another mechanism for those pods. The error is specifically happening in es-cluster-2.\n\nActually, this makes sense now—es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1 started 97 seconds ago and are still running with their original configuration, but es-cluster-2 \"failed to rejoin after restart\" because it's picking up the corrupted ConfigMap with the null node.name value. The solution is to fix the ConfigMap by removing or properly setting the node.name field. Since Elasticsearch 7.x defaults to using the hostname when node.name isn't specified, and StatefulSet pods get predictable hostnames, that should resolve the issue. the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` list. But I'm noticing the discovery seed hosts in the ConfigMap reference `.default.svc.cluster.local` when the namespace is actually `elasticsearch`, so those FQDNs should be `.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` instead. That's odd though - if the seed hosts were wrong, es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1 shouldn't have formed a cluster in the first place. The `node.name` null value is definitely what's crashing Elasticsearch before it even starts, while the seed hosts issue would only cause discovery problems later. I should check what services exist to understand the proper DNS configuration, then fix both the node.name and discovery.seed_hosts settings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1226,"cache_read_input_tokens":32426,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1226},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"73410223-d6e4-410e-933f-1b516cc62ad0","uuid":"95eeea4d-d47c-42a5-b990-6d96871e5d92","request_id":"req_011Cc53RvxpQfuBpPt31vGtK"}
